title: For Sale:  Ishapore Enfield in 7.62 NATO
postcontent:
I have an Ishapore Enfield 2A in 7.62 NATO.  This is a gun made at the British Enfield plant in Ishapore India when the Indian Army was changing over to the FN FAL. They were way down on the waiting list for delivery so they changed the plant over to manufacture rifles in 7.62 NATO. These were not remade .303s they were manufactured as 7.62MM with much stronger steel. When they were placed in storage by the Indian Army, they followed the British Army's practice and spray painted the rifles with black paint. (I believe this one of the reasons the British Empire is "not so much" anymore) All of this paint and the cosmoline soaked into the action has been stripped out and removed. It comes with a single 12 round magazine that has a matching serial number. It was the practice of the Indian Army to only issue one magazine per gun and reload via stripper clips instead. I also have 160+ rounds of 7.62 NATO I will throw in. $350.00 or best offer as long as the best offer is $350.00

Pictures are before the paint was removed.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 1893 Shotgun
postcontent:
Make: Winchester 
Model: 1893 
Serial Number: A 22549 
Year of Manufacture: 1896
Caliber: 12 Ga.
Action Type: Pump Action Shotgun 

The Model 1893 was/is solely a black powder gun only, and it was chambered for 2-5/8" shells only. It was never officially recalled, but Winchester did offer to replace it with a new Model 1897 if the owner so desired. If one was returned for repair work after August of 1897, a new Model 1897 was shipped to the owner and the Model 1893 was scrapped. The Model 1897 was factory chambered for a 2-3/4" smokeless powder 12-ga shell.

Approximately 34,145 Model 1893s were manufactured, and less than 25% of them survive today.

The World's Best Pocket Pistol
Fewer than 65,000 of these great pistols were made just after World War I, 
and of that number, fewer than 55,000 were chambered in .380 ACP. These pistols 
were in use long before Walther produced the PP or the PPK, long before Mauser produced
its HSc. Yes, this brainchild of John D. Pedersen was patented in 1915, with the first 
specimens coming out of the Remington factory in late 1918 (only 25 made that year). 
Production geared up in 1919, but in only eight years the Model 51 was relegated to the
history books, aside from a few assembled from parts after 1927.
So what is so remarkable about this little pistol? The intricate and flawless design; 
the "point your index finger" ergonomics; the exquisite workmanship - yes these features 
make the Remington 51 a really great pistol.What about the design? Isn't it just like all 
the other pocket pistols? NO! The Remington is far advanced compared to the simple blowback principle of other small pistols. It actually has a locking mechanism, allowing it to handle heavier cartridges in a lighter and slimmer package. This pistol is the only pistol ever produced using Pedersen's unique lockup design. In .380 ACP it weighs a scant 21 ounces. It's only 9/10" thick - very flat. Length overall is 6.625". The pistol lies very low in the hand for instinctive shooting.Ergonomics. Nothing compares to this pistol. Pedersenstudied hundreds of hands, taking wax impressions,in development of the shape of the grip. The pistol fits your hand like a glove. Workmanship. In this day of stampings, castings, and mouldings this little pistol of well-fitted milled parts, stands apart from all
the rest. Even as it approaches 100 years old the Remington 51 remains the leader of all pocket pistols.It has not been surpassed.

Seven shot 4" revolver and it's reliable, revolvers don't jam.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester Model 70 Short Rifle 102
postcontent:
Last bump WITH PRICE DROP!  

If no one wants it, so be it, I will keep shooting this great historic rifle and enjoy doing so.  Historic collectible firearms like this only come up for sale once or twice a lifetime and then disappear again for a generation or more before being seen again, maybe. 

Winchester Model 70 Short Rifle, .30-06, SN 102.  All of my research shows that this is the VERY FIRST Model 70 Short Rifle (CARBINE VERSION) produced by Winchester.  It was a hunter's rifle and shows the wear expected of a working man's dinner getter.  The stories it could tell from 79 years of hunting American game and putting dinner on the table.  Shoots perfectly, no issues at all.

The scope is a Weaver KV variable power and was installed by the original owner, the original rear sight is still intact and on the barrel, just reversed for the scope mounting.

$3200 FIRM cash price.  Even though this qualifies as a C&R firearm, transfer must take place at a FFL in the Fort Collins/ NorCO area, buyer pays fees.  I will ship to FFL at buyer's expense after USPS money order or personal check clears my bank.

Trades in state only at FFL in NorCO area.

I would really like a three gun set of Winchester lever actions:
9422 in .22LR, M94 in .357 Mag, M94 in .44 Mag in like new condition or,
A brace of Colt SAA Gen 2 in .357 Mag or .45LC in like new condition
